Targeting A Housing Subsidy

Jingyi Cai

November 03,2022

1. Motivation

Emil City is considering a more proactive approach for targeting home owners who qualify for a home repair tax credit program. By investing in credit, we can gain from the subsequent increase in house prices. Therefore, the focus of this projection is to identify the target group and give credit to those who can bring in revenue, so as to maximize our final revenue.

2.2 Data visualizations

In this section,
unemploy_rate: Unemployment rate at time of campaign Numeric
cons.price.idx: Consumer Price Idex at campaign time Numeric
cons.conf.idx: Consumer confidence index at time of campaign Numeric
inflation_rate: US Inflation Rate Numeric daily indicator
spent_on_repairs: Amoung annually spent on home repairs Numeric
y: Indicates the individual enter the program Category Yes/No (but you may wish to recode to numeric)
From this set of graphs, we can see that the greater correlation with entry into the program is the inflation rate and unemployment rate at the time. The interpretation is that more people who do not enter the programme tend to abandon this credict programme when inflation rate and unemployment rate are high.

3. Split your data into a 65/35 training/test set.

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(advertising$y_numeric, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
advertisingTrain <- advertising[ trainIndex,]
advertisingTest  <- advertising[-trainIndex,]
advertisingModel <- glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                  data=advertisingTrain%>%
                    dplyr::select(-y),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

summary(advertisingModel)
pR2(advertisingModel)

AIC: 505.21: same table, compare, smaller, better

3.1Make Predictions

We create a dataframe of predictions for the 500 observations in our test set, called testProbs.

These predictions are the estimated probabilities of clicking for these out-of-sample subjects. We can compare them to the observed outcome.

Run the code below and explore using glimpse(testProbs) to see what these predictions look like.

testProbs <- data.frame(Outcome = as.factor(advertisingTest$y_numeric),
                        Probs = predict(advertisingModel, advertisingTest, type= "response"))
testProbs <- 
  testProbs %>%
  mutate(predOutcome  = as.factor(ifelse(testProbs$Probs > 0.5 , 1, 0)))

response: on the scale of respond outcome: if clicked or not, probs: my prediction

ggplot(testProbs, aes(x = Probs, fill = as.factor(Outcome))) +

4. The Sensitivity (True Positive Rate) for a model with all the features is very low. Engineer new features that significantly increase the Sensitivity.

a. Interpret your new features in one paragraph.

In the new model, I create four features. As is shown in the first model, job and contact methods are important features for the result of programme. jobAvg for each job to use a continuous instead of categorical variable.
educationAvg for each education level to use a continuous instead of categorical variable. contactAvg for each contact method to use a continuous instead of categorical variable.
maritalAvg for state of marriage to use a continuous instead of categorical variable.

advertising2 <- 
  advertising%>% 
  group_by(job) %>% 
  summarize(totClicks = sum(y_numeric), 
            n = n(), 
            jobAvg = 100*(totClicks/n)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-n, -totClicks) %>%
  right_join(advertising, .)

For the ROC, the second model is a little bit more accurate than the previous one.
For our first model, we can find that the Specificity - the rate it correctly predicts no enter ( the true negatives ) does not generalize as well with respect to Sensitivity - the rate it correctly predicts entering ( true positives ). For the second model, after adding some features, the sensitivity is still high, and the specificity rose a a little. But it is still low. It means that we made many mistakes when predict for those who in fact do not enter this program. It seems our would-be decision-making tool is inconsistent in how it predicts the business-relevant outcome. That inconsistency could be systematic - perhaps it works better for younger residents, or the model could simply lack sufficient predictive power. Either way, this inconsistency will have a direct effect on the business process should this algorithm be put into production.

5.Output an ROC curve for your new model and interpret it.

The ROC curve, gives us another visual goodness of fit metric. One that is a bit more tricky. You want to have a curve that is above the y=x line, which is where your prediction rates for positives and negatives are no better than a coin flip. If its too square - you are probably over fit. We can see that in this figure, we can see that when flase positive is more than 0.5, the postive fractions rose slowly. The Area-Under-The-Curve or AUC calculation below will help guide your understanding of the ROC curve. A reasonable AUC is between 0.5 and 1. For this model, the AUC is 0.7734, which measn that

auc(testProbs2$Outcome, testProbs2$Probs)
ggplot(testProbs2, aes(d = as.numeric(Outcome), m = Probs)) +
  geom_roc(n.cuts = 50, labels = FALSE, colour = "#FE9900") +
  style_roc(theme = theme_grey) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, size = 1.5, color = 'grey') +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve - enterkModel")

6. Develop a cost benefit analysis.

a Write out the cost/benefit equation for each confusion metric.

Describe what each of the following mean in the context of our advertising use case:

True Positive: Count * 12400

False Positive:(-2850) * Count

True Negative:0

False Negative:0

b Create the Cost/Benefit Table as seen above.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs2 %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",Count * 12400,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count,0))))) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We correctly predicted no enter",
              "We correctly predicted an entering",
              "We predicted no click and customer entered",
              "We predicted a click and customer did not enter")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()

c Plot the confusion metric outcomes for each Threshold.

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs2 %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative",0 ,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",Count * 12400,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0 ,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", Count*(-2850),0)))),
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs2)
caret::confusionMatrix(testProbs2$predOutcome, testProbs$Outcome, 
                       positive = "1")

7.Conclusion

The distributions do not mean so much. In conclusion, I think the model could be put into prediction. Although in model2, which is the adjusted model, we found that its specificity(True Negative Rate) is very low, which means that we made many mistakes when predict those who in fact do not enter this program. However, the should also refer to the equation. In both positive or negative situation, the revenue is always 0, which means that it is ok to have a pretty low specificity. To this model, the most important thing is the sensitivity, because equation of the true positive or false positive are very different. In the model, the sensitivity is 0.98, which is pretty high.I think it will bring much revenue to the company. So, I think the data-driven approach improve outcomes relative to the business-as-usual approach. For the improvement of the model, I think it is important to find more features to improve the specificity and sensitivities, such as the duration of people live here. Plus, the contact method is also important for this program, so the company should try to improve the method and encourage more people to response to them.
